  <title>Time Controls</title>

  <p>
    Time controls add excitement and challenge to your games by limiting how long each player
    can think. You can configure time limits when starting a new game.
  </p>

  <section id="enabling">
    <title>Enabling Time Limits</title>

    <steps>
      <item><p>Start a <gui>New Game</gui></p></item>
      <item><p>Toggle <gui>Use Time Limit</gui> to ON</p></item>
      <item><p>Set <gui>Minutes Per Side</gui> (1-180 minutes)</p></item>
      <item><p>Set <gui>Increment</gui> in seconds (0-60 seconds)</p></item>
      <item><p>Choose <gui>Clock Type</gui>: Fischer or Bronstein</p></item>
    </steps>

    <note>
      <p>
        Without time limits, the timers display âˆž (infinity) and don't count down.
      </p>
    </note>
  </section>

  <section id="clock-types">
    <title>Clock Types</title>

    <terms>
      <item>
        <title>Fischer</title>
        <p>
          After completing a move, the increment is <em>added</em> to your remaining time.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Example:</em> With 5 minutes + 3 seconds increment:
        </p>
        <list>
          <item><p>You start with 5:00</p></item>
          <item><p>You use 10 seconds to make a move (4:50 remaining)</p></item>
          <item><p>3 seconds are added when you complete the move (4:53 remaining)</p></item>
        </list>
        <p>
          This allows you to accumulate time for later in the game.
        </p>
      </item>

      <item>
        <title>Bronstein (Delay)</title>
        <p>
          When your turn starts, there's a delay period before your clock begins counting down.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Example:</em> With 5 minutes + 3 seconds delay:
        </p>
        <list>
          <item><p>You start thinking</p></item>
          <item><p>The first 3 seconds don't count against your time</p></item>
          <item><p>After 3 seconds, your clock starts counting down</p></item>
          <item><p>If you move within 3 seconds, no time is deducted</p></item>
        </list>
        <p>
          This guarantees a minimum thinking time per move without accumulating extra time.
        </p>
      </item>
    </terms>
  </section>

  <section id="timer-display">
    <title>Timer Display</title>

    <p>
      The timers are displayed at the bottom-right of the window:
    </p>

    <list>
      <item><p><em>Red timer</em> - White background with black text</p></item>
      <item><p><em>Black timer</em> - Black background with white text</p></item>
      <item><p>The active player's timer counts down</p></item>
      <item><p>Format: minutes:seconds (e.g., 4:09, 0:45)</p></item>
    </list>
  </section>

  <section id="time-expiration">
    <title>Running Out of Time</title>

    <p>
      If a player's time reaches 0:00:
    </p>

    <list>
      <item><p>The game immediately ends</p></item>
      <item><p>A dialog appears: "Time's Up! [Player] ran out of time. [Opponent] wins!"</p></item>
      <item><p>The opponent is declared the winner by timeout</p></item>
    </list>

    <note style="important">
      <p>
        Make sure to manage your time wisely! Even if you have a winning position,
        running out of time results in an immediate loss.
      </p>
    </note>
  </section>

  <section id="timer-behavior">
    <title>Timer Behavior</title>

    <terms>
      <item>
        <title>Game Start</title>
        <p>
          Timers don't start counting until each player makes their first move.
        </p>
      </item>

      <item>
        <title>During Moves</title>
        <p>
          Only the active player's timer counts down. The opponent's timer is paused.
        </p>
      </item>

      <item>
        <title>When Paused</title>
        <p>
          Pressing the Pause button stops both timers until you resume.
        </p>
      </item>

      <item>
        <title>Undo/Redo</title>
        <p>
          Using undo/redo doesn't affect the timers - time spent thinking is not refunded.
        </p>
      </item>
    </terms>
  </section>

